<p>I'm struggling to understand why <code>intAt</code> will not work in this program. The goal of program is to simply convert weights for a specific planet.</p>  <pre><code>package weightonotherplanets; import java.util.Scanner;   public class WeightonOtherPlanets  {     public static void main(String args[]){              System.out.println("What is your weight on the Earth?");          Scanner weightInput = new Scanner(System.in); // Enter your weight         int weight = weightInput.nextInt();           System.out.println("1. Voltar\n2. Krypton\n3. Fertos\n4. Servontos\n"); // Choice of planets         System.out.println("    Selection?");          Scanner selectionChoice = new Scanner(System.in);         int selection = selectionChoice.nextInt();         int select = selection.intAt(0); // This is the problem in the code          switch (select)         {             case '1':                  System.out.println("Your weight on Voltor would be " + weight * 0.091);                 break;             case '2':                 System.out.println("Your weight on Krypton would be " + weight * 0.720);                 break;             case '3':                 System.out.println("Your weight on Fertos would be " + weight * 0.865);                 break;             case '4':                 System.out.println("Your weight on Servontos would be " + weight * 4.612);                 break;             default:                 System.out.println("Please make a selection.");          }     } } </code></pre>